crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)

crowdsourced_ids_results.rule_raw: alert ( gid:116; sid:58; rev:2; msg:"(tcp) experimental TCP options found"; metadata: policy max-detect-ips drop, rule-type decode; classtype:protocol-command-decode;)

attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, interpreter /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2, for GNU/Linux 2.6.9, not stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample is a sophisticated backdoor with multiple modes of operation. It can establish both direct (bind) and reverse (connect-back) shells over TCP, UDP, or raw ICMP packets for C2 communication. It uses RC4 to encrypt traffic. For stealth, it masquerades its process name as a legitimate service ('/usr/sbin/abrtd') and disables command history logging by setting HISTFILE to '/dev/null'.
